div.div:
Consequences of doing these opers non-atomically:
By the time a txn thread holds snap_commit_ver_hi_incl=x, the boundary between (x <--> x+1) might already have been erased.
Hence, conflict-checking yields false-conflicts at a higher probability, than if we read and held atomically. If done non-atomically, conflict-checking is guaranteed not to over-check (i.e. encroach into x and lower versions) iff there are zero concurrent commitments --- this defeats the main advantage of SSI wrt serial execution.
Possible enforcement of correctness:
It doesn't affect the correctness of the conflict-checking algo. When a conflict is found, we retry the transaction.
Should the group be atomic?:
Yes.

Txn sees P=x+1, and defines its initial snapshot as ( -inf ~ x+1 ].
But it does not traverse over a node with commit_ver=x+1.

If the txn is not read-only, it must eventually read commit_ver=x+1.
To do so, it must wait until nodes with commit_ver>=x+1 are pushed.
Meanwhile, it must not unhold the snapshot's list_ver; or else the commit_ver boundary (x <--> x+1) might disappear.

Txn refreshes P and sees P=x' > x+1.
It migt have to repeat the above indefinitely.

div.div:
The notification protocol:
Each txn notifies F+C about a non-held commit_ver iff this commit_ver can't yet be reached by walking from either of its nearest boundaries, i.e. iff both of its boundaries are either non-existent or held.
It is possible for F+C to receive a commit_ver that has been already popped off the
boundaries
hash-map. F+C ignores each such commit_ver.
If the
fc_avail
channel is at capacity, the sender does not re-attempt to send. Eventually every boundary will become non-held, and eventually F+C will discover all non-held boundaries by walking
boundaries
.
